  abstract = {We consider PAC learning of probability distributions (a.k.a. density estimation), where we are given an i.i.d. sample generated from an unknown target distribution, and want to output a distribution that is close to the target in total variation distance. Let \$\textbackslash mathcal F\$ be an arbitrary class of probability distributions, and let \$\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft F\textbraceright\textasciicircum k\$ denote the class of \$k\$-mixtures of elements of \$\textbackslash mathcal F\$. Assuming the existence of a method for learning \$\textbackslash mathcal F\$ with sample complexity \$m\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathcal\textbraceleft F\textbraceright\textbraceright ({$\varepsilon$})\$, we provide a method for learning \$\textbackslash mathcal F\textasciicircum k\$ with sample complexity \$O(\textbraceleft k\textbackslash log k \textbackslash cdot m\_\textbraceleft\textbackslash mathcal F\textbraceright ({$\varepsilon$}) \textbraceright/\textbraceleft{$\varepsilon$}\textasciicircum\textbraceleft 2\textbraceright\textbraceright )\$. Our mixture learning algorithm has the property that, if the \$\textbackslash mathcal F\$-learner is proper/agnostic, then the \$\textbackslash mathcal F\textasciicircum k\$-learner would be proper/agnostic as well. This general result enables us to improve the best known sample complexity upper bounds for a variety of important mixture classes. First, we show that the class of mixtures of \$k\$ axis-aligned Gaussians in \$\textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft R\textbraceright\textasciicircum d\$ is PAC-learnable in the agnostic setting with \$\textbackslash widetilde\textbraceleft O\textbraceright (\textbraceleft kd\textbraceright/\textbraceleft{$\varepsilon$}\textasciicircum{} 4\textbraceright )\$ samples, which is tight in \$k\$ and \$d\$ up to logarithmic factors. Second, we show that the class of mixtures of \$k\$ Gaussians in \$\textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft R\textbraceright\textasciicircum d\$ is PAC-learnable in the agnostic setting with sample complexity \$\textbackslash widetilde\textbraceleft O\textbraceright (\textbraceleft kd\textasciicircum 2\textbraceright/\textbraceleft{$\varepsilon$}\textasciicircum{} 4\textbraceright )\$, which improves the previous known bounds of \$\textbackslash widetilde\textbraceleft O\textbraceright (\textbraceleft k\textasciicircum 3d\textasciicircum 2\textbraceright/\textbraceleft{$\varepsilon$}\textasciicircum{} 4\textbraceright )\$ and \$\textbackslash widetilde\textbraceleft O\textbraceright (k\textasciicircum 4d\textasciicircum 4/{$\varepsilon$}\textasciicircum{} 2)\$ in its dependence on \$k\$ and \$d\$. Finally, we show that the class of mixtures of \$k\$ log-concave distributions over \$\textbackslash mathbb\textbraceleft R\textbraceright\textasciicircum d\$ is PAC-learnable using \$\textbackslash widetilde\textbraceleft O\textbraceright (d\textasciicircum\textbraceleft (d+5)/2\textbraceright{$\varepsilon$}\textasciicircum\textbraceleft -(d+9)/2\textbraceright k)\$ samples.},
